---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Pagination from '../../../components/Pagination.astro';
const base = '/portfolio';
const previous = 'huffman-compression';
const next = 'rslk';
---
<BaseLayout title="Hashes | ADEN Project" base={base}>
  <Pagination base={base} section="projects/aden" previous={previous} next={next} />
  <h1>Hashes</h1>

  <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
    <p>
      The Hashes project compares common hashing algorithms and evaluates how they behave for different input data. I studied techniques for fixed-size hashing, collision resistance, and distribution uniformity. This project bridged theory (modulo arithmetic, polynomial rolling) with practical benchmarking.
    </p>
    <img src={`${base}/images/hash-table.png`} alt="Hash table collision diagram placeholder" style="width:100%; max-width:720px; border-radius:12px; border:1px solid #ddd; margin-top:1rem;" />
  </section>

  <section id="hashing-algorithms" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
    <h2>Hashing Algorithms</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Reflection:</strong>
      <a href={`${base}/documents/reflections/pdf/${encodeURIComponent('Arnav Krishnan - Hash Analysis.pdf')}`} download target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hash Analysis (PDF)</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="analysis" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
    <h2>Summary of Hash Analysis</h2>
    <p>
      I benchmarked each algorithm on integer keys, short strings, and long text passages. The division method was fastest but had collision rates up to 30% with real-world data. Polynomial rolling hash had slightly higher computation cost but near-perfect distribution. The analysis reinforced that hash function choice depends on data type and performance requirements.
    </p>
    <p><a href={`${base}/documents/hash-analysis.pdf`} style="text-decoration:underline;" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View Full Hash Analysis (PDF)</a></p>
  </section>

  <section id="reflection">
    <h2>Key Learnings</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No single hash function is optimal for all use cases — speed vs. collision resistance is a tradeoff.</li>
      <li>Benchmarking with realistic data (not just synthetic tests) reveals unexpected collision patterns.</li>
      <li>Hash functions are foundational for dictionaries, caches, and cryptographic integrity checks.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>Reflection:</strong>
      <a href={`${base}/documents/reflections/pdf/${encodeURIComponent('Arnav Krishnan - Hash Analysis.pdf')}`} download target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hash Analysis (PDF)</a>
    </p>
    <p><a href={`${base}/aden-course`} style="color:#0055aa; text-decoration:underline;">← Back to ADEN Course</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>